You don&#39;t need to have a nested for loop in this case. There is a simpler way and far more readable.

You can loop through the `args` character array and add each letter character to a set. Once the set is created, loop through `myString` looking for matches in the set. If the character matches a character in the set, do nothing, otherwise append it to a `StringBuilder`. We can avoid creating a bunch of temporary `String` objects too, so we use `StringBuilder` instead of concatenating strings inside the loop.

Notice I added a lowercase and uppercase version of each character found in `arg`. This will make the check case-insenstive.

```java
public String remove(String arg) {
    if (myString == null || !isSet) {
        return &quot;&quot;;
    }
    
    // Create a set of characters to remove
    Set&lt;Character&gt; toRemove = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
    for (char c : arg.toCharArray()) {
        if (Character.isLetter(c)) {
            toRemove.add(Character.toLowerCase(c)); // add lowercase of the character
            toRemove.add(Character.toUpperCase(c)); // add uppercase of the character
        }
    }
    
    // concatenating strings inside a loop is a bad idea 
    StringBuilder newStr = new StringBuilder(); // use StringBuilder for better performance
    for (char c : myString.toCharArray()) {
        // Only remove it if it exists in the set
        if (!toRemove.contains(c)) {
            newStr.append(c);
        }
    }
    
    return newStr.toString();
}
```

Additionally, I am not sure if you have control over the instance variables or constructor, but there is really no need to track `isSet` or set `myString` to null. I would just create a constructor like below:

```java
public class CustomString {

    private String myString;

    public CustomString(String initialString) {
        this.myString = initialString;
    }
}
```

Unfortunately you have many problems in your code (mostly due to it&#39;s incomplete). But the following will fulfill the requirements of the remove method. It is presumed that `myString` and `isSet` are visible to the method.

- check special conditions
- allocate a StringBuilder object.
- convert argument string to lowercase
- iterate thru the character.
- if the index of the charsToRemove does not contain the char (i.e index == -1) then append it to StringBuilder
- when the loop finishes, return the StringBuilder as a string.

**Note:** it is important to preserve the original case when appending to the StringBuilder.
```
String myString = &quot;AbC@,123EfGh&quot;;

public String remove(String charsToRemove) {
    if(myString == null || myString.isEmpty() || !isSet) {
           return &quot;&quot;;
    }
      
    charsToRemove = charsToRemove.toLowerCase();
    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
       
    for (char ch : myString.toCharArray()) {
        if (!Character.isLetter(ch) || 
             charsToRemove.indexOf(Character.toLowerCase(ch)) == -1) {
                 sb.append(ch); 
        }
     }
     return sb.toString();
}

myString = remove(&quot;a3,Eh&quot;);
System.out.println(myString);
